#: src/rust-2024/reserved-syntax.md:1
msgid "Reserved syntax"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2024/reserved-syntax.md:3
msgid ""
"🚧 The 2024 Edition has not yet been released and hence this section is "
"still \"under construction\". More information may be found in the tracking "
"issue at <https://github.com/rust-lang/rust/issues/123735>."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2024/reserved-syntax.md:6
msgid "Summary"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2024/reserved-syntax.md:8
msgid ""
"Unprefixed guarded strings of the form `#\"foo\"#` are reserved for future "
"use."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2024/reserved-syntax.md:9
msgid "Two or more `#` characters are reserved for future use."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2024/reserved-syntax.md:11
msgid "Details"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2024/reserved-syntax.md:13
msgid ""
"[RFC 3593](https://rust-lang.github.io/rfcs/3593-unprefixed-guarded-strings."
"html) reserved syntax in the 2024 Edition for guarded string literals that "
"do not have a prefix to make room for possible future language changes. The "
"2021 Edition [reserved syntax](../rust-2021/reserved-syntax.md) for guarded "
"strings with a prefix, such as `ident##\"foo\"##`. The 2024 Edition extends "
"that to also reserve strings without the `ident` prefix."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2024/reserved-syntax.md:15
msgid "There are two reserved syntaxes:"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2024/reserved-syntax.md:17
msgid ""
"One or more `#` characters immediately followed by a [string literal](../../"
"reference/tokens.html#string-literals)."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2024/reserved-syntax.md:18
msgid "Two or more `#` characters in a row (not separated by whitespace)."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2024/reserved-syntax.md:20
msgid ""
"This reservation is done across an edition boundary because of interactions "
"with tokenization and macros. For example, consider this macro:"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2024/reserved-syntax.md:24
msgid "\"one token\""
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2024/reserved-syntax.md:25
msgid "\"three tokens\""
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2024/reserved-syntax.md:28 src/rust-2024/reserved-syntax.md:30
msgid "\"foo\""
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2024/reserved-syntax.md:29
msgid "r#\"foo\"#"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2024/reserved-syntax.md:34
msgid "Prior to the 2024 Edition, this produces:"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2024/reserved-syntax.md:43
msgid ""
"Starting in the 2024 Edition, the `#\"foo\"#` line and the `###` line now "
"generates a compile error because those forms are now reserved."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2024/reserved-syntax.md:49
msgid "Migration"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2024/reserved-syntax.md:51
msgid ""
"The [`rust_2024_guarded_string_incompatible_syntax`](../../rustc/lints/"
"listing/allowed-by-default.html#rust-2024-guarded-string-incompatible-"
"syntax) lint will identify any tokens that match the reserved syntax, and "
"will suggest a modification to insert spaces where necessary to ensure the "
"tokens continue to be parsed separately."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2024/reserved-syntax.md:53
msgid ""
"The lint is part of the `rust-2024-compatibility` lint group which is "
"included in the automatic edition migration. In order to migrate your code "
"to be Rust 2024 Edition compatible, run:"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2024/reserved-syntax.md:59
msgid ""
"Alternatively, you can manually enable the lint to find macro calls where "
"you may need to update the tokens:"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2024/reserved-syntax.md:62
msgid "// Add this to the root of your crate to do a manual migration.\n"
msgstr ""
